      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Escrow, in the context of buying a house, is a trust account that holds funds until certain conditions are met. It's a way to ensure that the funds are released only when the transaction is complete and all parties have fulfilled their obligations. You're not alone in feeling confused - it's a bit like a giant, invisible, and somewhat mysterious \"goblin\" that only appears when you need it most. Think of it like a temporary, escrowed \"goblin's hoard\" that holds your funds until the deal is sealed.\n\nIn Toronto, escrow accounts are typically set up for property taxes, insurance, and other costs associated with the property. The funds are usually held by a third-party escrow agent, who disburses the funds according to the terms of the agreement. It's a bit like having a \"goblin accountant\" who keeps track of all the money and makes sure everything gets paid on time.\n\nFor the closing, the escrow account is used to hold the down payment and other funds until the transaction is complete. Once the closing is finalized, the escrow agent releases the funds, and the \"goblin's hoard\" is disbursed. It's a bit like a magical, escrowed",
